{{Authority control}} [[Category:Research institutes in Germany]] [[Category:Geoscience institutes]]

'''Syngas fermentation''', also known as '''synthesis gas fermentation''', is a microbial process. In this process, a mixture of [[hydrogen]], [[carbon monoxide]], and [[carbon dioxide]], known as [[syngas]], is used as [[carbon]] and [[energy]] sources, and then converted into [[fuel]] and [[chemicals]] by [[microorganisms]].<ref name="Brown"/>
The main products of syngas [[fermentation (biochemistry)|fermentation]] include [[ethanol]], [[butanol]], [[acetic acid]], [[butyric acid]], and [[methane]].<ref name="Worden">Worden, R.M., Bredwell, M.D., and Grethlein, A.J. (1997). Engineering issues in synthesis gas fermentations, Fuels and Chemicals from Biomass. Washington, DC: American Chemical Society, 321-335</ref> Certain industrial processes, such as petroleum refining, steel milling, and methods for producing [[carbon black]], [[Petroleum coke|coke]], [[ammonia]], and [[methanol]], discharge enormous amounts of waste gases containing mainly CO and {{chem|H|2}} into the atmosphere either directly or through combustion. Biocatalysts can be exploited to convert these waste gases to chemicals and fuels as, for example, ethanol.<ref name="Abubackar">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1002/bbb.256 | last1 = Abubackar | first1 = H.N. | last2 = Veiga | first2 = M. C. | last3 = Kennes | first3 = C. | year = 2011 | title = Biological conversion of carbon monoxide: rich syngas or waste gases to bioethanol | url = http://ruc.udc.es/dspace/bitstream/2183/13730/2/Veiga_MariaCarmen_2011_CO_bioethanol_bioproducts.pdf| journal = Biofuels, Bioproducts and Biorefining | volume = 5 | issue = 1| pages = 93–114 }}</ref>
There are several microorganisms, which can produce fuels and chemicals by syngas utilization. These microorganisms are mostly known as [[acetogens]] including ''[[Clostridium ljungdahlii]]'',<ref name="Klasson">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0141-0229(92)90033-K | last1 = Klasson | first1 = K.T. | last2 = Ackerson | first2 = M. D. | last3 = Clausen | first3 = E. C. | last4 = Gaddy | first4 = J.L. | year = 1992 | title = Bioconversion of synthesis gas into liquid or gaseous fuels | url = | journal = Enzyme and Microbial Technology | volume = 14 | issue = 8| pages = 602–608 }}</ref> ''[[Clostridium autoethanogenum]]'',<ref name="Abrini">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1007/BF00303591 | last1 = Abrini | first1 = J. | last2 = Naveau | first2 = H. | last3 = Nyns | first3 = E.J. | year = 1994 | title = ''Clostridium autoethanogenum'', sp. nov., an anaerobic bacterium that produces ethanol from carbon monoxide | url = | journal = Archives of Microbiology | volume = 161 | issue = 4| pages = 345–351 }}</ref> ''[[Eubacterium]] limosum'',<ref name="Chang">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0032-9592(01)00227-8 | last1 = Chang | first1 = I. S. | last2 = Kim | first2 = B. H. | last3 = Lovitt | first3 = R. W. | last4 = Bang | first4 = J. S. | year = 2001 | title = Effect of CO partial pressure on cell-recycled continuous CO fermentation by ''Eubacterium limosum'' KIST612 | url = | journal = Process Biochemistry | volume = 37 | issue = 4| pages = 411–421 }}</ref> ''[[Clostridium carboxidivorans]]'' P7,<ref name="Ahmed">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1002/bit.21305 | last1 = Ahmed | first1 = A | last2 = Lewis | first2 = R.S. | year = 2007 | title = Fermentation of biomass generated syngas:Effect of nitric oxide | url = | journal = Biotechnology and Bioengineering | volume = 97 | issue = 5| pages = 1080–1086 | pmid = 17171719 }}</ref> ''[[Peptostreptococcus]] productus'',<ref name="Misoph">{{Cite journal | last1 = Misoph | first1 = M. | last2 = Drake | first2 = H.L. | year = 1996 | title = Effect of CO2 on the fermentation capacities of the acetogen ''Peptostreptococcus productus'' U-1 | url = | journal = Journal of Bacteriology | volume = 178 | issue = 11| pages = 3140–3145 | pmid = 8655492 | pmc = 178064 }}</ref> and ''Butyribacterium methylotrophicum''.<ref name="Henstra">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.copbio.2007.03.008 | last1 = Henstra | first1 = A.M. | last2 = Sipma | first2 = J. | last3 = Reinzma | first3 = A. | last4 = Stams | first4 = A.J.M. | year = 2007 | title = Microbiology of synthesis gas fermentation for biofuel production | url = | journal = Current Opinion in Biotechnology | volume = 18 | issue = 3| pages = 200–206 | pmid = 17399976 }}</ref> Most use the [[Wood–Ljungdahl pathway]].
Syngas fermentation process has advantages over a [[chemical process]] since it takes places at lower [[temperature]] and [[pressure]], has higher [[Chemical reaction|reaction]] [[Chemical specificity|specificity]], tolerates higher amounts of [[sulfur]] compounds, and does not require a specific ratio of CO to {{chem|H|2}}.<ref name="Worden" /> On the other hand, syngas fermentation has limitations such as: * Gas-liquid mass transfer limitation<ref name="Henstra"/> * Low volumetric [[productivity]] * Inhibition of [[organisms]].<ref name="Brown" /><ref name="Worden" />
